        <!-- Slide 1: Introduction -->
        <div class="slide active" id="slide1">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>Introduction to EDI</h2>
                
                <div class="definition-box">
                    <h3>What is EDI?</h3>
                    <p>Electronic Data Interchange (EDI) is the computer-to-computer exchange of business documents in a standard electronic format between business partners. EDI replaces postal mail, fax, and email, enabling organizations to electronically transmit information that was traditionally communicated on paper, such as purchase orders, invoices, and shipping notices.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="quote-box">
                    "EDI is the backbone of modern e-commerce, enabling seamless business-to-business transactions across the global digital economy."
                </div>

                <h3>Historical Context</h3>
                <p>EDI was developed in the 1960s and became standardized in the 1970s with the introduction of ANSI ASC X12 standards in North America and EDIFACT standards internationally. The technology has evolved significantly with the advent of the internet and cloud computing, making it more accessible and affordable for businesses of all sizes.</p>

                <div class="stats-container">
                    <div class="stat-box">
                        <div class="stat-number">85%</div>
                        <div class="stat-label">Fortune 500 companies use EDI</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="stat-box">
                        <div class="stat-number">70%</div>
                        <div class="stat-label">Reduction in processing time</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="stat-box">
                        <div class="stat-number">50%</div>
                        <div class="stat-label">Cost savings on average</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="stat-box">
                        <div class="stat-number">99%</div>
                        <div class="stat-label">Accuracy improvement</div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h3>Core Principles</h3>
                <div class="grid-2col">
                    <div class="card">
                        <div class="card-icon">📋</div>
                        <h4>Standardization</h4>
                        <p>EDI uses standardized formats such as ANSI X12, EDIFACT, and XML to ensure that all parties can understand the transmitted data regardless of their internal systems.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card">
                        <div class="card-icon">🔄</div>
                        <h4>Automation</h4>
                        <p>Documents are automatically transmitted, received, and processed without human intervention, significantly reducing manual data entry and associated errors.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card">
                        <div class="card-icon">🔒</div>
                        <h4>Security</h4>
                        <p>EDI transactions are secured through encryption, digital signatures, and secure protocols ensuring data integrity and confidentiality.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card">
                        <div class="card-icon">⚡</div>
                        <h4>Speed</h4>
                        <p>Electronic transmission enables real-time or near-real-time business document exchange, dramatically improving supply chain efficiency.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 2: Architecture -->
        <div class="slide" id="slide2">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>EDI System Architecture</h2>

                <div class="architecture-diagram">
                    <h3 style="text-align: center; margin-bottom: 30px;">Layered EDI Architecture</h3>
                    
                    <div class="diagram-layer">
                        <h4>1. Application Layer</h4>
                        <p>Business applications (ERP, CRM, WMS) that generate or consume business documents. This layer includes enterprise systems like SAP, Oracle, or custom applications.</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="diagram-layer">
                        <h4>2. Translation Layer</h4>
                        <p>EDI translation software converts internal data formats to standardized EDI formats (X12, EDIFACT) and vice versa. This layer handles data mapping and transformation.</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="diagram-layer">
                        <h4>3. Communication Layer</h4>
                        <p>Protocols and networks used to transmit EDI documents. Common methods include AS2, SFTP, VAN (Value-Added Network), FTP, and HTTP/HTTPS.</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="diagram-layer">
                        <h4>4. Security Layer</h4>
                        <p>Encryption, authentication, and digital signatures ensure data security. Includes SSL/TLS protocols, PGP encryption, and certificate-based authentication.</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="diagram-layer">
                        <h4>5. Business Partner Layer</h4>
                        <p>Trading partner agreements, profiles, and relationships. Defines rules, standards, and protocols agreed upon between business partners.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h3>EDI Components</h3>
                <div class="grid-2col">
                    <div class="card">
                        <h4>EDI Standards</h4>
                        <ul class="feature-list">
                            <li><strong>ANSI X12:</strong> North American standard for industries</li>
                            <li><strong>EDIFACT:</strong> International standard by UN</li>
                            <li><strong>XML:</strong> Modern web-based standard</li>
                            <li><strong>TRADACOMS:</strong> UK retail sector standard</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card">
                        <h4>Transmission Methods</h4>
                        <ul class="feature-list">
                            <li><strong>VAN:</strong> Value-Added Network services</li>
                            <li><strong>AS2:</strong> Secure internet-based protocol</li>
                            <li><strong>SFTP:</strong> Secure File Transfer Protocol</li>
                            <li><strong>Web EDI:</strong> Browser-based EDI access</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

